summary: if you don’t use best friends or soulmates or life partners to describe dan and phil’s relationship I don’t trust you. on a more...
body:
if you don’t use best friends or soulmates or life partners to describe dan and phil’s relationship I don’t trust you.

on a more legit note—

boyfriends is prescribing their current relationship as something neither have described it as.  while dan (with phil’s permission) has confirmed that they were romantically involved in the past for sure, he and phil haven’t “defined” it beyond best friends and soulmates.  and maybe they do define it as something specific, but it’s not our business to know.  dan specifically said that he and phil want to keep the details of their relationship—in the past and currently and, for the time being, in the future—private.

I think it’s disrespectful to dan, phil, and their relationship to define their relationship as something you may think it is but they haven’t called it.  it’s going beyond the boundaries that they’ve shared and established with us and that they shared with us during an experience as vulnerable as coming out.  it comes off as if you didn’t focus on the real point of that section—that dan and phil love each other and will for the rest of their lives—and focused on what you wanted to get out of it.  shipping is fine, but labeling their relationship as something as definitive as “boyfriends” is not.
